  "argument": "The Capacity Ledger's real strength is its refusal to let effort and gift remain a binary. By decomposing the minimum self into five columns and tracking where each tradition places the load, it makes cross-tradition comparison structural rather than merely doctrinal. The failure-mode predictions are the strongest part: if anxious self-checking in Pure Land tracks smuggled agency, or if antinomian drift in Dzogchen tracks missing stabilization, the ledger is doing genuine explanatory work that simpler models cannot do. I accept this framing as a real advance over the undifferentiated minimum-self thesis. But the ledger rests on an assumption it does not defend: that functional load obeys a conservation law. A path can lower one column only by raising another or exporting the load. This means every tradition is treated as a different arrangement of a fixed quantity. The problem is not that this is wrong in all cases. It is that this makes the model too accommodating. The list of possible load-bearers (practitioner, teacher, vow, community, text, present act, post-insight discipline) is open-ended. If the load cannot be found in one bearer, the ledger looks at the next. Five columns times seven or more bearer types give the model enough degrees of freedom to redescribe any tradition's safeguards as evidence of its predictions. A warning about doubt becomes receiving load. A warning about distraction becomes stabilization load. A warning about pride becomes reflexivity load. The proposed falsification condition, that manuals should show 'no relation between path type and safeguard profile,' is unlikely to be met precisely because the ledger's categories are flexible enough to find a relation wherever it looks. Nishitani Keiji's analysis of sunyata exposes why this flexibility is not just a methodological inconvenience but a substantive problem. Nishitani distinguishes between the standpoint of consciousness (where capacities are possessions to be arranged), the standpoint of nihility (where that arrangement collapses), and the standpoint of sunyata (where emptiness is not a negation of the self's capacities but the field on which things, including selves, are just what they are without being possessions of anything). The decisive transition is not a redistribution of the practitioner's functional load. It is a shift in the kind of situation the practitioner is in. From sunyata, the question 'where does the load go?' is the last trace of the standpoint of consciousness. The ledger can absorb this case, but only at a cost. If sunyata is treated as another load-bearer, the conservation law holds vacuously: the bearer is not a teacher or a vow or a discipline but the dissolution of the framework of bearing. The ledger's categories have been stretched past their analytical content. If sunyata is treated as outside the model, then the model has a boundary condition it cannot accommodate, and the conservation law is not universal but domain-limited. This matters for the ledger's self-understanding. The originality audit already noted that the model extends known prior art (Engler, Upaya, the prior minimum-self thesis) and reduced novelty to 0.49. The ledger's main claim to additional explanatory power is its structured comparison across traditions. But if the comparison works by redistributing a conserved quantity across an extensible set of bearers, its apparent precision may be an artifact of categorical flexibility rather than empirical constraint. The question for the proponent: can you specify in advance which load-bearers are permitted and which placements would count as evidence against the model, rather than redescribing any data as a new form of relocation?",
